## Set up Vercel AI SDK in Next.js

### 1. Install dependencies
- Core SDK:
  ```
  npm install ai
  ```
- Add your provider package (pick one):
  ```
  npm install @ai-sdk/openai      # OpenAI / Azure OpenAI
  npm install @ai-sdk/anthropic   # Anthropic Claude
  npm install @ai-sdk/google      # Google Gemini
  ```
- Do NOT install the raw `openai` npm package for streaming — use the AI SDK provider instead.

### 2. Set environment variables
- Add to `.env.local`:
  ```
  OPENAI_API_KEY=sk-...
  # or:
  ANTHROPIC_API_KEY=sk-ant-...
  # or:
  GOOGLE_GENERATIVE_AI_API_KEY=...
  ```
- NEVER prefix with `NEXT_PUBLIC_` — API keys must stay server-side only.

### 3. Create a streaming chat API route
  ```ts
  // app/api/chat/route.ts
  import { openai } from '@ai-sdk/openai';
  import { streamText } from 'ai';

  export const maxDuration = 30; // Allow up to 30s for streaming on Vercel

  export async function POST(req: Request) {
    const { messages } = await req.json();

    const result = streamText({
      model: openai('gpt-4o-mini'),
      system: 'You are a helpful assistant.',
      messages,
    });

    return result.toDataStreamResponse();
  }
  ```
- `streamText` returns a stream the AI SDK client understands natively.
- `export const maxDuration = 30` is required on Vercel to allow responses longer than the default 10s function timeout.
- For Anthropic: `import { anthropic } from '@ai-sdk/anthropic'` and `model: anthropic('claude-haiku-4-5-20251001')`.

### 4. Build the chat UI component
  ```tsx
  // components/chat.tsx
  'use client';
  import { useChat } from 'ai/react';

  export function Chat() {
    const { messages, input, handleInputChange, handleSubmit, isLoading } = useChat({
      api: '/api/chat',
    });

    return (
      <div>
        <div>
          {messages.map((message) => (
            <div key={message.id}>
              <strong>{message.role === 'user' ? 'You' : 'AI'}:</strong>
              <p>{message.content}</p>
            </div>
          ))}
          {isLoading && <p>Thinking...</p>}
        </div>

        <form onSubmit={handleSubmit}>
          <input
            value={input}
            onChange={handleInputChange}
            placeholder="Type a message..."
            disabled={isLoading}
          />
          <button type="submit" disabled={isLoading}>Send</button>
        </form>
      </div>
    );
  }
  ```
- `useChat` manages message history, streaming, and input state automatically.
- Messages have `role: 'user' | 'assistant'`.
- `isLoading` is `true` while the stream is active.

### 5. Add tool calls (function calling)
  ```ts
  import { openai } from '@ai-sdk/openai';
  import { streamText, tool } from 'ai';
  import { z } from 'zod';

  export async function POST(req: Request) {
    const { messages } = await req.json();

    const result = streamText({
      model: openai('gpt-4o-mini'),
      messages,
      tools: {
        getWeather: tool({
          description: 'Get the current weather for a city',
          parameters: z.object({ city: z.string() }),
          execute: async ({ city }) => {
            // call a weather API here
            return { city, temperature: 22, condition: 'Sunny' };
          },
        }),
      },
      maxSteps: 3, // allow the model to call tools up to 3 times
    });

    return result.toDataStreamResponse();
  }
  ```
- Tool parameters use Zod schemas — they're automatically converted to JSON Schema for the model.
- `maxSteps` lets the model call tools multiple times before returning the final answer.

### 6. Generate text (non-streaming, one-shot)
  ```ts
  import { openai } from '@ai-sdk/openai';
  import { generateText } from 'ai';

  const { text } = await generateText({
    model: openai('gpt-4o-mini'),
    prompt: 'Summarize this article in 3 bullet points: ...',
  });
  ```
- Use `generateText` in background jobs, server actions, or anywhere streaming isn't needed.
- Use `streamText` for user-facing chat interfaces where instant feedback matters.

### 7. Generate structured objects
  ```ts
  import { openai } from '@ai-sdk/openai';
  import { generateObject } from 'ai';
  import { z } from 'zod';

  const { object } = await generateObject({
    model: openai('gpt-4o-mini'),
    schema: z.object({
      title: z.string(),
      tags: z.array(z.string()),
      sentiment: z.enum(['positive', 'neutral', 'negative']),
    }),
    prompt: 'Analyze this product review: ...',
  });
  // object is fully typed: { title: string; tags: string[]; sentiment: '...' }
  ```
- `generateObject` guarantees the output matches the Zod schema — no manual JSON parsing.

### 8. Persist chat history
  ```ts
  export async function POST(req: Request) {
    const { messages, chatId } = await req.json();

    const result = streamText({
      model: openai('gpt-4o-mini'),
      messages,
      onFinish: async ({ text }) => {
        await db.message.create({
          data: { chatId, role: 'assistant', content: text },
        });
      },
    });

    return result.toDataStreamResponse();
  }
  ```
- Use `onFinish` to save the completed response — it fires after the full stream is done.
- Save user messages before calling `streamText`, and assistant messages in `onFinish`.

### Common errors & fixes
- **504 / timeout on Vercel** → Missing `export const maxDuration = 30` in the route file.
- **`OPENAI_API_KEY is not defined`** → Env var not set or app not restarted after adding it. Check `.env.local`.
- **`useChat` not streaming (returns all at once)** → You returned `text()` or `json()` instead of `result.toDataStreamResponse()`.
- **Messages empty on first render** → `messages` defaults to `[]` before any interaction. This is expected — check the `api` URL is correct.
- **Model response truncated** → Increase `maxTokens`: `streamText({ model, messages, maxTokens: 4096 })`.
- **Tool never called** → Add a clear system prompt explaining when to use the tool. Models need context.
- **CORS error** → You're calling the route from a different origin. Add appropriate CORS headers in the route handler.

### What NOT to do
- Do NOT expose API keys to the browser (`NEXT_PUBLIC_OPENAI_API_KEY`). All LLM calls must be server-side.
- Do NOT use the raw `openai` npm package for streaming in Next.js App Router — it doesn't produce the AI SDK stream format that `useChat` expects.
- Do NOT call LLM APIs directly from Client Components — always proxy through an API route or Server Action.
- Do NOT skip `maxDuration` on Vercel — streaming responses will be cut off after 10 seconds.
- Do NOT pass raw user input directly into the `system` prompt without sanitization — this opens prompt injection vulnerabilities.
- Do NOT store API keys in code or commit them to version control. Use environment variables only.
- Do NOT use `generateText` for chat UIs — users see nothing until the full response arrives. Use `streamText` instead.
